a, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wavrin","type":"LAST","meanings":["An old name. The same as Waring or Guerin, who came over with the Conqueror; a name probably connected with that of the Waernas or Wernas. the Varini or Verini, a people of the Elbe"],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hildegarde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an old Germanic female personal name composed of <i>hild</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’. It was borne by the second wife of Charlemagne and by the mystical writer  Hildegard  of Bingen (  1098–1179 ), in whose music and writings there has been great interest in recent decades."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hildegarde de Wavrin was born in 1172, in Wavrin, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France, her father, Hellin de Wavrin, was 65 and her mother, Comtesse Torsella D'Arras, was 28. She married Baudouin I TOURNAI in 1184. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1224, in Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1172–1224":"1172–1224","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1175–1197":"1175–1197","–Male":"Surnud","1158–1208":"1158–1208","1165–1208":"1165–1208","1185–1221":"1185–1221","1190–1226":"1190–1226","1107–1169":"1107–1169","1144–1203":"1144–1203","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","1175":"1175","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1107":"1107","APRÈS 1221":"pärast 1221","1226":"1226","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1158":"1158","21 MAY 1208":"21. mai 1208","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","1221":"1221","1208":"1208","Le Roeulx, Hainaut, Belgique":"Le Roeulx, Hainaut, Belgia","Wavrin, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Wavrin, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calai